COMBINED WORK NOTICE — GPL v3 + AGPL v3

Some files in this work were originally contributed under the GNU General
Public License version 3 (GPL v3). Those contributions retain their original
GPL v3 license. AetherSDR contains additional files licensed under the GNU
Affero General Public License version 3 (AGPL v3), making the entire
combined work subject to the network-use requirements of AGPL v3 section
13, as expressly permitted by GPL v3 section 13.

Practically, this means:

  * If you modify AetherSDR and convey those modifications (by copy,
    binary, or source distribution), the modified source must be made
    available to the recipient — this requirement comes from GPL v3.

  * If you modify AetherSDR and provide users access to the modified
    program over a network (for example, by hosting AetherSDR as a
    remote SDR service, paid or free), the modified source must be made
    available to those network users — this requirement comes from
    AGPL v3 section 13.

The full text of both licenses is provided:

  * LICENSE-AGPL-v3.txt   — GNU Affero General Public License version 3
  * LICENSE-GPL-v3.txt    — GNU General Public License version 3

The two licenses are compatible and intentionally combined under this
mechanism. The AGPL v3 file is the canonical license for new contributions
to AetherSDR; future contributors agree to license under AGPL v3 via the
Contributor License Agreement (see CLA.md).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

WHY AGPL v3

AetherSDR is a Linux-native SmartSDR-compatible client for FlexRadio SDRs.
FlexRadio Systems publishes their own SmartSDR client under an End User
License Agreement that requires a separate commercial license for any use
that "directly or indirectly generates revenue, compensation, or other
commercial benefit" (SmartSDR for Windows EULA, revised January 19, 2026).

AetherSDR's previous GPL v3 license inadvertently created a workaround for
that commercial protection: an operator could run AetherSDR (no EULA) as
the engine of a paid remote-SDR-as-a-service offering without sharing
their modifications. The AGPL v3 network-use clause closes that gap by
requiring source disclosure for network-delivered services. This aligns
AetherSDR's licensing posture with FlexRadio's stated commercial position.

This change does not affect non-commercial personal use, community forks,
or modifications used privately. It does affect operators who host
modified AetherSDR as a remote service for others.

